metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #100
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Emotional Shell #19
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 72 · 54 · 40 · 30 · 24 · 20 every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted, and then drop one price tier.

---------

The feeling of being human – with all of its intricate hopes, struggles, and fleeting emotions – seems so unique that we assume artificial intelligence could never replicate our experience. And while we devise systems for solving unfathomably complex problems, generating algorithmic creativity, and unlocking regenerative biological possibilities, we simultaneously cling to the power and originality of emotional feeling – believing it to be the irreplaceable source of what makes us human.

If the body is our shell for emotion and soul, can an artificial humanoid be another vessel for these thoughts and feelings – for human essence itself? If our ‘soul’ is the last stand between us and the machines, what happens when the soul becomes transferable? That we may see answers to these questions looks more real every year, and is perhaps a little frightening. 

Emotional Shell uses introspective portraits of future selves to question what it means to be human, when the people around us are no longer human.

---------

Warning: This piece is GPU intensive, it may not render on lower end devices.

Press 1-3 to select from low, medium, and high quality settings
Press 'S' to save the image at the current scale
Press 'H' to save the image at 2400px resolution

Created with Three.js
For third party license information, please see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt

---------

metadata.name: Boro #5
metadata.description:
Boro is inspired by the Japanese mending technique of the same name, which means something mended, in particular something mended with small pieces of fabric and patterned over stitching. The technique makes the fabric both stronger and more beautiful.

To render at different resolutions please use keyboard characters 1 to 5, which will render the artwork at a square of 1000 to 5000 respectively.

metadata.name: Across Paper Stones #18
metadata.description:
Wherever you want to go, you'll find a path to take you there.

Each tile is made up of two deformed rectangles. One is drawn with a drifting, fragmented outline.

Over thirty color palettes are shuffled together on each output, helping form slight edges between groups.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Starmap - AI Study I #18
metadata.description:
Starmap brings you to different sectors of the generative art galaxy. A first of its kind generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow, which involves writing text prompts that get translated into javascript code. This project was created with English words and human imagination, but the programming of the piece is all AI.

The code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing some Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #1 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: Capsule #127
metadata.description: Capsule is an exercise in constraints. Capsule uses minimal visual elements. These elements have different colors, size, placement and duplicated elements.
